entry.title: [Hub] Fix thumbnail capture sequencing
entry.content:
HubLayout was trying to show Hub before requesting thumbnail captures.

While this is supported it led to the tab switcher panes fetching a

stale thumbnail. The thumbnail is stale because usually when showing

the Hub we do a fresh thumbnail capture to get an up-to-date image for

the shrink expand animation, the Tab Switcher was using whatever

thumbnail was already on disk prior to this new capture.



Invert the sequencing using a Promise so that the

thumbnail can be captured before we try to create the Hub (thus

requesting the thumbnails for the tab switcher) and before we hide the

tab. Then the callback for the animation can be serviced anytime after

the promise is fulfilled before we start the animation.

entry.title: Restore base::ProtectedMemory
entry.content:
This PR restores parts of the base::ProtectedMemory code removed in

https://crrev.com/c/1891114 . This is done as part of a larger effort

to harden MojoJS bindings against data-only attacks. Out of multiple

proposed approaches for preventing MojoJS bindings from being enabled

by a data-only attack, using protected memory appears to provide the

best balance of security versus cost/maintenance burden. A follow-up

PR will be made to actually use base::ProtectedMemory for this purpose.



Since there are challenges with using base::ProtectedMemory on Linux and

MacOS (originating from changes that make it so that a memory section

that is going to be made writable during runtime cannot be made

read-only at compile/link time), this PR only restores the functionality

at Windows for now. If the use of it to harden the MojoJS binding

enablement proves effective, restoring it for Linux and MacOS can be

revisited.

entry.title: Create "OpenXrExtensionHandler" Architecture
entry.content:
Creates the notion of an OpenXrExtensionHandlerFactory and list that can

be used to automatically append required extension names to be queried

from and enabled on the OpenXr runtime. It will also serve as the source

of truth for prioritzation of extensions that can handle multiple

features. Also converts the existing extensions onto this pattern.



The actual "Extension handlers" themselves need to be used as

themselves, and as such creating a base ExtensionHandler class doesn't

really make sense. It was briefly considered to allow them to simply

append whatever data they needed to onto a frame data struct if

enabled, but different needs for constructors and even some usage

patterns such as subscribing to hit tests still require enough knowledge

of the concrete type, that adding a common base type there doesn't

seem valuable. However, the chained pairs and repetition of the pattern

in OpenXrExtensionHelper is not ideal either; but template

specialization wouldn't necessarily save us code, and using macros to

stamp out the mostly identical methods is discouraged (to say the least)

by the styleguide.



While no factory currently supports multiple webxr features, due to the

usage patterns, the scene understanding manager will almost certainly

be the place that planes are supported from, so `GetSupportedFeatures`

returns a vector to avoid a refactor if/when that implementation comes

along.

entry.title: [AsyncSB] Fix race between unsafe resource callback is scheduled and executed.
entry.content:
It is possible that DidFinishNavigation is called between

PendingCheckerCompleted is scheduled[1] and executed. In this case,

PendingCheckerCompleted thinks that DidFinishNavigation is not called,

so it will set show_interstitial_after_finish_navigation_ to true,

which AsyncCheckTracker::DidFinishNavigation is supposed to read later

to decide to show a warning.



The case we're fixing here is that it's possible for DidFinishNavigation

to be called before the scheduled PendingCheckerCompleted call is

executed, so this CL gives PendingCheckerCompleted the ability to show

the warning itself.

entry.title: Rename //net/base/mac directory to //net/base/apple (2/n)
entry.content:
This renames the remaining directory in //net/base used both by macOS

and iOS, following the naming convention and changing it something more

suggestive.



Like suggested by mark@, this renaming process will be carried on in

three steps:



1. Rename net/base/mac to net/base/apple, creating new temporary

forwarding headers in net/base/mac that #include net/base/apple.



2. Convert all of the use sites from net/base/mac to net/base/apple.

This can be done across multiple ch anges if desirable, which could make

things more manageable for reviewers. The changes here are performing

this step in //chrome and //ios/chrome directories, using the following

command:

LC_CTYPE=C find . -type f -exec sed -i "" "s:net/base/mac/:net/base/apple/:g" {} \;



3. Remove the temporary forwarding headers in net/base/mac, so that

we‚Äôre only left with net/base/apple.

entry.title: Batch process positive patterns
entry.content:
Currently, each regex is a giant OR of regexes for every language. With

PatternProvider, a single regex per language is used instead.

Unfortunately, it turns out that calling the regex engine with one

larger regex is faster than multiple smaller regexes.



To improve the PatternProvider performance, this CL thus concatenates

the smaller regexes at runtime* to again just make a single call.



This is complicated by the fact that the regex matching logic also

depends on the MatchAttribute of the regex, describing whether it should

apply label, name, etc. of the field. For this reason, the CL batches

regexes by their set of MatchAttribute, before joining them and calling

the regex engine.



This improves the runtime of the go/heuristic-classification-tests on my

cloudtop from ~18 secs to ~12 seconds (without pattern provider it takes

~9 seconds). The fact that the output doesn't change also serves as an

additional test that this change is correct.



* This can't be done at compile time, since we only consider a subset

of regexes, depending on the page language.

entry.title: [Fuzzing] Prefer OWNERS files over git blame.
entry.content:
gen_fuzzer_owners.py is used to generate a FOO.owners file for every

fuzzer executable FOO we build (in a certain configuration).



The historical approach ever since crrev.com/c/1028668 was to use

`git blame` to find "the author of FOO" and save that to FOO.owners.



For code in `third_party` (git submodules), a simple `git blame`

invocation from `chromium/src` does not work. Instead, the nearest

OWNERS file is located instead. This behavior was introduced in

crrev.com/c/3039004.



This CL aims to use the second approach (locate OWNERS file) for all

code by default, falling back to `git blame` only in case of failure.



Why? The chromium repo has grown such that running `git blame` for every

single fuzzer is very slow. The hope is that finding OWNERS files is

much faster, as well as probably less surprising.



While it would be nice to remove the git blame logic, this CL attempts

to touch as little as possible to first prove this approach works.

entry.title: Throw exceptions for malformed operations while layers are opened
entry.content:
Since layers are only filtered and composited into their parent bitmap

once the layer is closed, operations that access bitmap pixels are

malformed if there are layers open.



This can happen when reading the pixels from the canvas (for example

with `getImageData`) or directly overwriting pixels (with

`putImageData`).



With this change, exceptions are thrown for these operations when used

with open layers. Promises also fail in the case of `createImageBitmap`

and `convertToBlob`. Some APIs already had this behavior, but this CL

extends that logic to all APIs accessing bitmap pixels.



The existing tests for unclosed layers had to be moved to manual, since

for the offscreen and worker cases the generator uses methods that now

throw exceptions.

entry.title: Sync prefs: Make kIOSChromeSyncablePrefsAllowlist constexpr
entry.content:
Before this CL, kIOSChromeSyncablePrefsAllowlist was created via

MakeFixedFlatMapNonConsteval, which is discouraged since it does

sorting at runtime. Instead, MakeFixedFlatMap should be used which

does the sorting at compile time, but requires all the inputs to be

constexpr.

This CL updates all the relevant pref definitions to `inline constexpr`,

which allows `MakeFixedFlatMap` to be used. (It's also arguably

preferable anyway - the pref definitions are now all in one place, the

header, rather than split across .h and .cc/.mm.)
